So if you want to test it out, I'm going

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.120
to try to launch this by the end of the conference.

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.280
But you do need to follow me on Blue Sky.

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:49.500
That's not intentionally manipulative.

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:52.400
It's just the easiest way that I have to limit the

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:54.760
number of people using it right now.

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:57.040
I don't feel like doing an invite system.

00:02:57.060 --> 00:03:01.700
And then my professional world, I'm a CTO of

00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:02.260
a startup.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:06.850
The title is fancier than the actual what I'm doing

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:09.100
day-to-day.

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:10.660
What I'm doing day-to-day is actually building

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:12.300
just sort of like accounting software.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:17.920
So if you have QuickBooks data and you want dashboards

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:18.980
, I can do that.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:23.310
But before I joined the startup world, I was doing consulting

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:25.650
for eight years, which is why I talk about enterprise data

00:03:25.650 --> 00:03:25.840
.

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:31.700
So the thing that's interesting about the enterprise data space,

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:33.640
and like I told you that I'm a data scientist.

00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:34.980
I came from an R&D background.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.480
Like I peaked in Fortran.

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:39.780
I'm not like one of these web people, right?

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:41.040
And if you look at the AT proto, or I'm

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:43.090
sorry, at proto, I learned that it's at proto

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:43.300
.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:46.040
I thought it was actually Austria proto for a while.

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:53.660
If you look at the tooling, it's in TypeScript

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:55.790
, it's in Go, and if you're really cool

00:03:55.790 --> 00:03:56.620
, it's in Rust.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:00.110
And those are like the hip languages, right?

00:04:00.140 --> 00:04:03.700
And those aren't the languages that data people use.

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:08.440
But it's also reflective of the mindset that at proto developers

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:11.480
have, which is that when you're building web applications,

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.140
you're treating data like a hot potato.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:15.050
Like data comes in, you want to like get rid of

00:04:15.050 --> 00:04:16.420
it as quickly as you can, right?

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:19.260
Because the longer that you're holding on to data and processing

00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:22.580
it and doing things to it, the harder your system becomes

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:24.840
to maintain and operate at scale, right?

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:29.240
And so web developers have built all of these really cool tools

00:04:29.260 --> 00:04:31.240
and languages, and they're like really hip.

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:33.530
We've got these really cool conferences in places like the University

00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:36.210
of British Columbia, and they wear jeans to work, and

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:37.980
they're really like awesome, right?

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.930
And data people are kind of different than that.

00:04:43.320 --> 00:04:46.680
Like they kind of emerge from the world of database administrators,

00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:49.750
and database administrators are famous for being grumpy, and they

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:51.800
don't like change, and they don't like you,

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:53.400
and they don't like your fancy languages.

00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:55.420
Like we're all toiling in the SQL minds.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:57.540
We might be writing some Python.

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:01.410
If you're really like fancy, you might do a little

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:03.060
Scala or Spark in the data space.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:07.110
And a lot of these folks are sitting there maintaining systems that

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.690
have been around for 25 years, and they're like not

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:11.880
wearing jeans and hoodies to work.

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:14.020
They're wearing like khakis and polos because they have

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:16.440
serious jobs, and they're holding serious data that all of

00:05:16.450 --> 00:05:20.370
these like multi-billion companies will stop operating if anything

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:21.520
happens to it.

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:22.900
So they don't want to do change.

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:25.870
They don't want to do a lot of fancy technology development

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:26.120
.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:28.240
And this is a little bit of hyperbole.

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:31.300
I have known database administrators who from time to time do wear

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:31.800
jeans.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:37.410
The thing about enterprise data is that it's not really technology

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:38.080
development.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:39.300
It's anthropology.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:42.780
Because when you're dealing with a company that has been around

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:46.900
for 20, 30, 50, 100, 150, sometimes

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.960
longer years, the information that you have is all historical.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:56.200
And it reflects the relationships of a business, its departments,

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:58.940
its entities, its customers, and its suppliers.

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:03.320
You all are probably familiar with Conway's law that the

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:08.220
architecture of a system reflects the communication patterns of a company.

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:12.500
Well, that all comes through in enterprise data.

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:15.280
I've actually worked with data systems that you can pinpoint the

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:18.140
exact day that two teams stop talking to each other.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:21.560
And you can do that because the fields change.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:26.580
And then you have to carry around this conditional with a magically

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:27.500
coded date.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:34.280
Because on June 16th of 2007, these two teams went

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:35.340
through a reorg.

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:38.800
And then all of your logic has to carry that through for

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:39.510
all time.

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:44.120
And so this is like an anthropological problem which makes sharing

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:48.180
and using this data and doing anything meaningful with it very,

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:49.140
very difficult.

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:52.580
So what is the problem with enterprise data?

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:55.200
The problem is that data access is slow, it's difficult

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:56.500
, it's expensive.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:07:00.000
So is the analysis, so is the data engineering.

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:03.200
I've gone to data engineering teams as a consultant.

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:04.520
I said, tell me about your problems.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:05.700
They said, well, here's our backlog.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:08.930
And I said, you know, how many tickets do you

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:10.060
do each week?

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:12.560
And they said, week, that's ambitious.

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:15.720
We do maybe 20 tickets per quarter.

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:17.920
And they said, well, how many new tickets per quarter

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:18.300
do you get?

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:18.920
They say 40.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:21.760
So that's not a solution.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:23.950
That's not like a situation that's getting better, right

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:24.040
?

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:27.940
And then you also see things like data science seems like early

00:07:27.940 --> 00:07:31.170
, mid-2000s, everyone's like, oh,

00:07:31.180 --> 00:07:33.350
you've got to have data scientists because AI is coming,

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:33.880
right?

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:36.160
So they went out and they like pulled all of these people

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:38.020
out of like academia, right?

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:41.050
A lot of neuropsych people, a lot of like

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:44.950
astronomy, physics, all of that, people who know like

00:07:44.950 --> 00:07:45.740
good mathy stuff.

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:46.580
And they put them in a team.

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.540
They didn't really explain to them how to work in an

00:07:48.540 --> 00:07:49.920
enterprise environment.

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:52.480
And so they built a lot of stuff that was really cool

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:54.180
, but it wasn't in phase of product development.

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:57.360
And so then you have like these really cool algorithms that nobody

00:07:57.360 --> 00:07:58.280
knows how to deploy.

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.780
Nobody knows how to run the code for it.

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:04.250
And by the time they actually get it, they're like

00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:06.610
six months out of date anyways, so it doesn't actually

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:07.200
add value.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:12.340
And then like data folks don't really do agile.

00:08:12.620 --> 00:08:16.190
Like version control, like they're still clicking tools, like

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:18.820
building ETL pipelines with drag and drop, right?

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:21.420
Like continuous delivery isn't a thing.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.170
CD, it's like a thing that you put music on

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:23.340
.

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:27.540
And DevOps is a fancy team to data folks that nobody can

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:28.240
explain, right?

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:30.940
Like the data folks, they don't really understand how to

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:34.000
do rapid, fast, agile software development.

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:35.920
Again, hyperbole, because a lot of things are

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:36.580
getting better.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:39.150
But if you go into an enterprise, there's still a

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:40.800
lot of stuff where they don't even know how to use

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:41.060
Git.

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:45.160
I've actually gone into clients at big companies and had like

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:46.830
day one, I'm like, all right, let's

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:47.700
talk about your architecture.

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:49.850
And by day three, I'm like, okay, here

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:51.120
's how to do Git status.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:57.490
And the problem is that like within software development, we favored

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:58.620
software developers.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:01.800
We've given them a lot of tools to build software really

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:02.300
quick.

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:04.280
And a lot of what we've done is we've absol

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:07.460
ved them of the duty and the responsibility to care about things

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:10.290
like data quality, data semantics, the relevance of the

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:10.900
data, right?

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:12.640
We're just like, here, keep, get the data

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:13.740
quick, throw it somewhere.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:16.630
And then they're pushing it to Kafka streams and stuff like

00:09:16.630 --> 00:09:16.900
that.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:17.560
And it's all great.

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:18.920
It's great for them.

00:09:18.940 --> 00:09:22.900
And then some data engineer has to sort out that mess.

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:27.340
And we've tried solving this with like lots of different architect

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:27.640
ures.

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:29.920
If you talk to data people, they love talking about architecture

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:30.060
.

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:32.580
We've gone from data warehouses to data lakes.

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:33.980
Data lakes became data swamps.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.280
We've built things like data vaults, which is,

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:40.460
I guess, if you really want to make your data model

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:41.920
complicated, data vault is great.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:45.130
We've added Greek letters to it, a Lambda architecture or

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:46.180
a Kappa architecture.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.110
And this has all gone sort of in a cyclical pattern

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:51.560
, right?

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:55.780
This shift between centralization and decentralization.

00:09:55.800 --> 00:10:00.120
And so what happens is most enterprises are like, we need

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:00.680
a big database.

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:02.580
So they build a big database.

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:03.940
And they're like, here's our data warehouse.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:04.620
It's OLAP.

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:05.360
It's all this stuff.

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:07.810
And then there's a bottleneck and there's a backlog

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:07.960
.

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:09.800
And so they say, this isn't working.

00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:12.640
And then finally somebody with enough political clout in the organization

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:13.720
is like, screw you all.

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:14.750
I'm building my own database.

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:16.820
And then that happens once.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:18.030
And then the next team's like, well, they did

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:18.200
it.

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:18.860
So I'm going to do it.

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:21.430
And so the next thing you know, like you're three

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:23.320
, four or five years later, and now you've got

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:24.820
the shadow IT situation going on.

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:26.440
There's all of these different data systems.

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:28.720
And somebody goes, why are we spending all this money on

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:29.340
data systems?

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:31.160
Let's do another big consolidation.

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:34.020
I've come in on the back end of $100 million

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:37.490
failed data architecture consolidation projects, right?

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:39.480
Tons of money go into this.

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:43.900
It's all been very expensive and nothing has worked.

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:45.220
Nothing has worked.

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:49.830
Sometimes things get a little bit better, but every organization I

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.680
talk to has the same exact problems, right?

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:55.510
And so when I was at ThoughtWorks, we came

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:59.780
up with this solution that I'm going to talk about.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:01.980
But a little bit about why it doesn't work.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:03.540
Sorry, I almost skipped a slide here.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:07.270
You just have this situation of like data governance is a mess

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:07.500
.

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:09.880
Data catalogs are all kind of terrible.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:12.780
Schematics are discombobulated.

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:14.020
Semantics are even worse.

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:15.400
Like systems don't talk to each other.

00:11:15.420 --> 00:11:16.560
People don't talk to each other.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:20.310
It's just a bad situation like for most of the time

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:20.620
.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:24.140
And what we actually need is a scalable and consistent way to

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:28.540
define the exchange of data between organizations, systems, parties,

00:11:28.540 --> 00:11:30.730
companies, whatever.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:33.190
We need platform independence, right?

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:36.100
So we have systems, you know, lots of companies are

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:39.310
like, we're going to be on Azure and AWS and

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:41.200
Google because we don't want to put all our eggs in

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:41.700
one basket.

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.780
And now you have three different types of ecosystems.

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:45.920
It's like Tower of Babel.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:47.540
Nobody's speaking the same data language.

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:51.100
And we need lightweight oriented models, right?

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:54.660
So when I was at ThoughtWorks, we came up

00:11:54.720 --> 00:11:56.000
with this idea called data mesh.

00:11:56.020 --> 00:11:57.430
Data mesh is a bit like communism.

00:11:57.460 --> 00:11:59.040
It came out of conditions.

00:11:59.060 --> 00:12:05.070
And the conditions that we talked about were all of this like

00:12:05.070 --> 00:12:09.650
fragmented ecosystem of, you know, not having this way

00:12:09.650 --> 00:12:11.900
, this common way of defining what it is that you mean

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:13.020
when you're talking about data.

00:12:13.040 --> 00:12:15.110
So if you don't know what you're talking about when

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:18.100
it comes to data, you don't know how to even

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:21.460
describe a way to share and exchange it.

00:12:21.480 --> 00:12:25.080
So data mesh came up with, it's a decentralized model

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:28.230
of working with data that focuses on data as a product,

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:28.800
right?

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:31.290
So we actually wanted to think about like, what if you

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:33.670
worked with big data in the same way that you work with

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:36.200
microservices, which is kind of a nonsensical

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:38.920
way of thinking about it because microservices are designed to be

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:42.400
really, really small and big data is like, by definition

00:12:42.400 --> 00:12:43.280
, very, very big.

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:47.040
So we came up with these ideas of like, okay,

00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:48.760
let's make data a product.

00:12:48.780 --> 00:12:51.660
Well, when you're doing microservices development, you're

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:52.830
usually domain oriented.

00:12:52.860 --> 00:12:56.310
You usually have a platform like Kubernetes or something to deploy your

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:57.100
service on.

00:12:57.580 --> 00:12:59.340
And then of course, everyone said, well, that doesn

00:12:59.370 --> 00:12:59.820
't work.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:00.620
We need to govern it.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.640
And so then we stapled on federated computational governance to

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:08.160
make them happy and then try to like figure out what that

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:08.900
was going to be.

00:13:10.300 --> 00:13:12.340
And this is a really great theory.

00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:14.590
Again, data meshes like communism is really great in theory

00:13:14.590 --> 00:13:14.780
.

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:19.930
The practice has been a little bit less stellar in some cases

00:13:19.930 --> 00:13:20.620
, right?

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:24.280
Because domain oriented data products, they're a good idea,

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:27.540
but we haven't given anyone the tools of how to actually

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:29.560
do it and implement it correctly.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:36.630
So what if we just pretended like those challenges didn't exist

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:36.820
?

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:39.260
Like what if we just decided that we're going to start

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:41.880
from scratch we're not going to talk about all of your

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:44.000
semantic layer, we're not going to talk about all of

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.360
your legacy systems, we're just going to build a micros

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:47.260
ervice around data.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:49.780
What would that look like?

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:51.760
It's actually not that bad of an idea.

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:55.980
The problem is once you start to try to implement that,

00:13:55.980 --> 00:13:58.180
everything falls apart.

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:00.840
The tooling sucks, the data catalogs suck.

00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:03.380
It requires a ton of platform engineering.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:05.040
Nothing is really set up for this, right?

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:08.830
Like there's no standard language for defining what a data product

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:11.000
is or how it should interact.

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:15.060
There's no standard way of like joining the semantics from

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:16.640
two different domains together.

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:19.880
And there's a lot of languages that have come up like

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:23.060
OWL and RDF and all this other stuff to try

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:27.060
to define how data looks and how data should be shaped.

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:30.420
But they have all of these gaps about how we're supposed

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:32.700
to, defining how we're supposed to work with data.

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:37.340
So when you actually dive into, and this is where we

00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:39.090
get to lexicon, there's a little bit of

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:40.540
Chekhov's gun that I'm setting up here.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:44.660
If you look at the way that we model data, we

00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:46.920
care about really two things.

00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:48.900
We look at the nouns and the verbs.

00:14:48.920 --> 00:14:52.970
The nouns are what the data means, how it's structured

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:55.500
, who owns it, who can access it, what are

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:56.600
the permissions, etc.

00:14:57.860 --> 00:15:01.220
And sometimes those have adjectives like the type of the data

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:04.390
or the frequency that it's updated, the freshness of

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:05.380
it, things like that.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:09.180
And then we also have, so I'll jump into the

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:11.740
verbs in a second, but this is a great example of

00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:13.320
talking about the nouns.

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:18.860
So I pulled this like random OWL 2 definition off of

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:21.940
, I don't know, the internet somewhere, which is

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:23.100
great.

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:26.200
It's talking about the physical quality of the thermal energy of

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:28.790
a system, and it defines all of this like really specific

00:15:28.790 --> 00:15:29.180
stuff.

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:31.640
Half of the characters, solidly more than half of the

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:35.500
characters in here are metadata, like meta metadata about like the

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.630
lengths of like where to find the actual thing that you're

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:38.920
seeing.

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:42.920
And so this is really cool if you want to know that

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:47.620
like this number is about the physical quality of the thermal energy

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:49.740
of a system, but it doesn't tell you what that

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:51.520
means in any sort of context, right?

00:15:51.540 --> 00:15:53.380
It doesn't tell you what you should do about it or

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:54.540
why you should care about it.

00:15:56.800 --> 00:16:00.470
So the problem with that type of approach and the problem with

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:03.720
all of those types of data specification languages that we've seen

00:16:03.740 --> 00:16:05.580
is that they tend to be very static.

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:08.690
It assumes that data is fully self-contained, that

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:11.380
you can just kind of like look at a thing and describe

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:13.760
its properties and be like, aha, I now have a

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:15.740
perfect platonic ideal of a chair.

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:18.680
I've defined exactly what a chair is, but you don

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:21.100
't talk, like you don't do anything about like how

00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:22.560
a chair should be used, right?

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:27.200
And then on top of that, it becomes really difficult to

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:31.370
start to contextualize it because in reality, you need to

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:36.420
start to think about how these nouns become composed with each other

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:38.380
, how they interplay, right?

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:41.580
And so there's some stuff out there working on how to

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:46.560
overlay different data definition languages in a practical systems context, but

00:16:46.560 --> 00:16:49.640
we're still missing the whole like action element of it.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.800
The thing is with like building a microservice style architecture,

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:57.720
you also need to define those verbs.

00:16:57.740 --> 00:17:00.320
You need to define how these services interact.

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:02.360
That's actually the critical thing about it.

00:17:02.380 --> 00:17:06.420
If you look at something like the open API spec, it

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:07.540
's really great.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.720
It talks about how you access the data, what to do

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:12.780
with the data, what are the things that you can,

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:16.170
like how do you write it, update it, delete it

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:16.560
, whatever.

00:17:16.580 --> 00:17:18.420
You define your API spec.

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:20.700
It tells you exactly like this is going to be a put

00:17:20.700 --> 00:17:22.530
, this is going to be a get, this is going

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:23.460
to be a post, whatever.

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:27.880
How to request permission for the data is often part of that

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:31.860
like broader spec and how systems should handle the data, right

00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:31.970
?

00:17:31.990 --> 00:17:38.440
And so you can do that with those tools, but if

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:42.140
you start looking at things like open API, then they start

00:17:42.140 --> 00:17:46.620
to sort of fall away on the definitions of the nouns,

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:47.320
right?

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:51.050
So open API is great because it gives you a little bit

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:54.600
of a shape of the data, but beyond sort of the

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:58.830
basic sort of JSON types and it's really limited in that

00:17:58.830 --> 00:18:01.820
case, it doesn't really tell you about what the data

00:18:01.820 --> 00:18:03.520
means in a broader context, right?

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:12.980
So all of this sort of ecosystem of defining data through these

00:18:12.980 --> 00:18:17.520
sort of specification languages, all of this also omits this

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:19.580
concept of domain ownership whatsoever.

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:23.260
You're basically just saying data exists, here it is,

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:24.940
or systems exist, here they are.

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:27.660
We're not really talking about how to access them, who

00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:29.760
owns them, what they should do about them.

00:18:30.500 --> 00:18:32.600
So if you're going to build a good data product language

00:18:32.600 --> 00:18:35.400
, you need to have a concrete encoding of your domain ownership

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:39.140
, so who owns this, what do they own it for

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:42.330
, you need to have a clear and concise, an ext

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:46.040
ensible definition of the nouns, and a flexible, versionable

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:47.580
definition of the verbs.

00:18:47.600 --> 00:18:50.440
So you need to be able to encode change over time

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:52.820
, you need to be able to encode what it is

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:54.680
that you're describing, and who owns it.

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:55.800
So those three things are key.

00:18:55.820 --> 00:19:02.280
As I mentioned, Data Mesh was a great idea for

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:07.520
trying to put together these data products, but it really suffered

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:08.950
from four key flaws.

00:19:08.980 --> 00:19:11.540
The first of it is, if you know ThoughtWorks

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:13.370
at all, ThoughtWorks tended to be a little bit

00:19:13.370 --> 00:19:13.860
dogmatic.

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:16.140
It was a criticism of the company as long as I worked

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:19.360
there that existed even before I worked there.

00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:22.880
And Data Mesh was like, we were trying to do

00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:26.070
everything with microservices, and so we just sort of almost

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:30.580
naively applied that to a really big data architecture project.

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:34.040
And this existed, there's like no tooling for it,

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:37.440
there's no equivalent to Kubernetes for standing up like a massive

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:42.480
, large-scale data processing system, aside from Kubernetes,

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:45.040
which is really difficult if you've ever actually tried to do

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:47.920
big data processing in Kubernetes, like running Spark in Kubernetes is

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:49.000
really difficult.

00:19:49.020 --> 00:19:53.940
A lot of change, like again, Data Mesh,

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:56.760
it requires a lot of re-education, right?

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:58.600
The way that you work with data, the way that your

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:00.660
data people are actually doing things.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:03.120
You have to teach them DevOps, you have to teach them

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:05.140
Agile, you have to teach them domain ownership.

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:07.200
Really difficult.

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:11.090
And then we also spent the last like decade decoupling

00:20:11.090 --> 00:20:14.320
software devs from any downstream responsibility for their data, and

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:15.730
now we're turning around and saying, oh wait, no

00:20:15.730 --> 00:20:16.100
, no, no.

00:20:16.120 --> 00:20:18.460
now you have to be responsible for that again.

00:20:18.480 --> 00:20:20.820
And they didn't really like that.

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:26.650
So, I mentioned that we need, you know, all

00:20:26.650 --> 00:20:31.750
of these definitions around nouns and verbs and domain ownership and stuff

00:20:31.750 --> 00:20:32.220
like that.

00:20:32.240 --> 00:20:35.000
And yes, this is now Chekhov's gun going

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:36.660
off, because if you look at lexicon, you

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:41.040
look at the spec, it actually kind of elegantly solved

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:42.880
all three of those problems and I don't even think that

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:43.560
it was trying to.

00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:49.660
The first thing that it will do is this reverse DNS addressing

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:50.480
is brilliant.

00:20:50.480 --> 00:20:56.360
This solves a huge problem for the enterprise data space because now

00:20:56.360 --> 00:21:01.340
you can actually encode your domain ownership literally in a domain

00:21:01.340 --> 00:21:05.180
, like a domain name solution.

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:08.920
And you're able to, you can do that across an

00:21:08.980 --> 00:21:10.240
entire organization, right?

00:21:10.260 --> 00:21:13.620
So you can actually set up an organization, give every department

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:16.530
, every team, whatever, a path in that domain name

00:21:16.530 --> 00:21:20.240
, reverse it, and then they can host their own le

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:20.680
xicons.

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:24.900
It does come up with the definition of the nouns.

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:27.060
This is actually, I don't know if you noticed when

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:29.780
I started it, I decided, I was really bored,

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:33.160
so I decided yesterday, instead of doing like Google Slides

00:21:33.160 --> 00:21:36.040
, I would build my own slideshow system on at Pr

00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:36.620
oto.

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:42.610
So I vibration-coded a slideshow system.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:44.900
This is the lexicon for the slideshow.

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:48.510
And so you can see that there's, the nouns are

00:21:48.510 --> 00:21:49.420
defined here.

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:51.930
I need a title, I need a short description, I

00:21:51.930 --> 00:21:54.160
need maybe a timestamp when it's created.

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:56.400
All of that is there and it's contextual.

00:21:56.420 --> 00:22:00.700
It's not just the data type, like the JSON data

00:22:00.700 --> 00:22:01.100
type.

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:03.440
Of course, that is in there, but it tells me

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:05.680
what the meaning of that data is and why it's relevant

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:07.020
and why I should care about it.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:09.960
And if I had gone a little bit farther, I would

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:12.790
have been able to put the verbs in here as well for

00:22:12.790 --> 00:22:17.160
how to author a slideshow, how to assign permissions to

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:19.250
a slideshow, how to revoke permissions to a slides

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:19.560
how.

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:22.960
So I could turn this into essentially a Google Docs or

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:25.820
the Google Slides type of situation or a PowerPoint type of

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:30.220
situation by encoding what the actions are directly in the lex

00:22:30.220 --> 00:22:30.570
icon.

00:22:30.580 --> 00:22:38.720
So, again, I mentioned this kind of casually solved

00:22:38.740 --> 00:22:42.620
all three of those problems, which would be a really big

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:46.030
benefit for an enterprise because not only does that mean that if

00:22:46.030 --> 00:22:48.700
you can define a lexicon for your data products,

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:52.910
you can start sharing that data across your organization but also outside

00:22:52.940 --> 00:22:55.540
of your organization if you want to publish those lexicons

00:22:55.540 --> 00:22:56.080
openly.

00:22:56.100 --> 00:22:59.020
And this is, by the way, not even talking about

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:01.500
using the PDS as your platform.

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:04.280
Like, I'm not necessarily talking about like, oh,

00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:07.060
replace your data platform with a PDS and everything will be

00:23:07.060 --> 00:23:07.490
solved.

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:12.740
I'm actually just talking about use a flexible data definition language

00:23:12.750 --> 00:23:16.640
that gets away from all of the sort of dogmatism

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:20.580
of ontologies and all of that stuff and focus on actually

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:25.170
shareability rather than like fully fleshing out the definition

00:23:25.170 --> 00:23:25.300
.

00:23:25.310 --> 00:23:28.320
This is a standard way of doing it.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:33.310
I think Emily Hunt spoke about this yesterday, like sharing exploding

00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:40.080
stars data through a globally accessible standardized feed that every astronomy lab

00:23:40.100 --> 00:23:44.760
in the world can subscribe to and then see the exact data

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:48.360
format for that data without having to go through and set up

00:23:48.380 --> 00:23:51.270
their own Kafka consumers, without having to run a Kafka cluster

00:23:51.270 --> 00:23:52.080
, all of that stuff.

00:23:52.100 --> 00:23:53.860
That's a really compelling idea.

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:57.350
It's a really, really, really brilliant way of being

00:23:57.350 --> 00:24:01.580
able to make that data available in a way that people can

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:04.700
not just access it but understand what it means.

00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:09.380
So then this, like when I look at Lexicon,

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:11.240
actually the first time I saw Lexicon, I said,

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:14.230
I've been trying to develop this as a data product specification

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:17.160
language for the last three years and here it is.

00:24:17.180 --> 00:24:19.040
So it's worth exploring.

00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:22.880
I think that this is actually relevant because if you know me

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:25.660
from any of my other work, you know that I don

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:32.110
't really like fascists and one of the problems in the

00:24:32.110 --> 00:24:34.580
data space is that I've mentioned this sort of cyclical

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:35.060
behavior.

00:24:35.080 --> 00:24:39.250
We've gone from data warehouses to data lakes to streaming

00:24:39.250 --> 00:24:42.460
architectures and back again and the trend right now is towards

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:46.000
consolidation and so you see companies like Palantir who go

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:49.180
up to these big organizations and government agencies and they say,

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:54.840
we can solve your data consolidation problems and I've never known

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:57.680
anyone who's used Palantir who likes it, right

